Secure Design Principles 

1. Principle of Least Privilege 
    

Ensure that people only have enough access that they need to do their job! 

By ensuring that accounts have only the privileges necessary to do their job, you ensure that if an attacker compromises an account, you minimize what information they can access. 

2. Separation of Duties 
    

No single role should have too much authority! 

When someone does a job that is too big, we fall right back to the point where they will need lots of permissions to do that job. Also, when someone has many duties in their job, it means that they are susceptible to making poor decisions. 

3. Defense in Depth 
    

Assume that any security system you put in place is going to fail! 

A classic defense-in-depth security implementation contains a wide range of security elements including: 

- Endpoint security solutions – antivirus software and endpoint detection and response (EDR) tools to protect threats originating from servers. 
    
- Patch management tools – to keep endpoint operating systems and applications up-to-date and address common vulnerabilities and exposures (CVEs). 
    
- Network security solutions – firewalls, VPNs, VLANs, etc. 
    
- Intrusion detection/prevention (IDS/IPS) tools – to identify malicious activity and thwart attacks. 
    
- User identity and access management solutions – single sign-on, multi-factor authentication, and lifecycle management tools to authenticate and authorize users.

Security Testing 

Security testing is a process intended to identify flaws in the security controls of an information system that protect data and maintain functionality as intended. It is an important practice that gives organizations visibility into real-world threats to the security of their systems. 

Security tests allow finding the gaps in application security before a hacker does so by exploiting vulnerabilities. 

There are three common approaches to security testing: 

- Black-box - in this case the security tester has no knowledge of the system being tested like a real hacker who does not know internal details of the application. This approach is suitable if you want to simulate a situation close to real. 
    

- White-box - this approach could be used if you want to find the maximum number of vulnerabilities and misconfigurations in the application. In this case it is necessary to provide the security tester with the access to the application source code, documentation, administrative areas, and to conduct an application walkthrough to understand all the nuances of the application. 
    

- Grey-box - a mixed approach which assumes that a tester has partial knowledge of application’s internal workings and a certain level of access. This choice could help to achieve a better balance in test coverage and needed effort.

Step 1: Define the scope 

What will be the target of security testing? Which functional and technical aspects should be tested? What depth of testing is recommended? Usually on this step the security tester conducts a meeting with stakeholders to have answers to these questions. 

What needs to be audited? 

1. Identifying most important data 
    
2. Identifying the attack surface 
    
3. Defining testing priorities 
    
4. Choosing the vulnerability testing approach 
    
5. Confirming a user role matrix 
    

How to audit the targets? 

1. Black Box, Grey Box, White Box: Which approach? 
    
2. How to estimate the time needed for testing? 
    

Step 2: Information gathering 

Information gathering is the first and foundation step in the success of security testing. The more useful information a security tester has about a target, the more he or she can find vulnerabilities in the target and find more serious problems in the target by exploiting them (to demonstrate). 

Step 3: Analysis & planning 

Applications can have a large attack surface, so it is important to prioritize goals, such as specific business risks, to guide the depth of the security testing. In addition, the security tester needs to analyze all available information to select the most optimal testing methodologies, determine a list of potential vulnerabilities based on the technologies used in the application, select right vulnerability scanners and tools for manual security testing. 

Step 4: Vulnerability testing 

Vulnerability testing helps identify vulnerabilities in the application and supporting infrastructure before a compromise can occur and provide recommendations on how to fix the vulnerabilities found. There are four testing approaches: 

1. Security test cases 
    

Security test cases are used to test security requirements. The method of creating security cases based on requirements was discussed in the “security requirements” chapter. 

If there is no budget for other types of security testing, then this is an ideal option to write security test cases that QA engineers can perform. 

2. Vulnerability assessment 
    

A vulnerability assessment is a systematic review of security weaknesses in an information system. It evaluates if the system is susceptible to any known vulnerabilities, assigns severity levels to those vulnerabilities, and recommends remediation or mitigation. 

In comparison with security test cases, vulnerability assessment not only checks compliance with the requirements but tries to find as many as possible vulnerabilities and misconfigurations in the application. 

Best choice for almost all types of projects. 

3. Penetration testing 
    

A penetration test not only tries to find all the vulnerabilities in the system but also exploits them to determine how deeply an attacker can penetrate the system and what maximum damage can be done to the application. Usually, the main purpose of this type of testing is to obtain the highest privileges on the system such as ROOT or NT AUTHORITY \ SYSTEM 

Suitable for all types of projects. 

4. Red teaming 
    

Red teaming is usually a team task of testing all available infrastructure, which includes advanced security testing techniques, specially designed hacking tools, as well as all possible methods of hacking the system, social engineering, phishing, and in some cases even physical penetration into the company where the project is being developed. 

Best for testing very large projects or company infrastructure. Allows simulating a real attack and an assessment of the current defense of the project/company. Also, this type of testing is used to train the internal security team from the actions of real attacks. 

Step 5: Report writing 

Strong report writing is an effective tool for communicating with a customer. As a security tester this can be especially beneficial for communicating what you have done when testing hardened applications. The report gives an opportunity to explain what the application’s maturity level is, and what kind of work was performed during the engagement. 

We will focus on two aspects and components of writing an effective report: 

1. Executive summary 
    

Security test reports typically begin with a high-level summary of the findings. This executive summary is often intended to be a concise overview of the results meant for company executives, who are looking for actionable takeaways without needing to dig into the entirety of the report. 

This summary reveals where the security testers bypassed your security controls and what they were able to uncover within your systems. 

It also spells out recommendations for security improvements, including what they advise you to secure first, followed by other short, medium, and long-term goals for enhancing your enforcements. 

2. Assessment findings 
    

It describes each phase of their attack process and how the security testers went about compromising the application system. 

The section will explain how the security testers were able to perform all of their activities, and how they got into the system. It’s all there that you’ll see the full description, to understand the context of how the attack was performed and the resulting gaps in the project security. 

For example, this section has these topics for each identified issue: 

- Name of the found vulnerability 
    
- Risk rating 
    
- Summary with impact 
    
- Affected functionality 
    
- Proof of Concept 
    
- Recommendations how to fix it 
    

Step 6: Remediation testing 

Within a reasonable period of time following the conclusion of a security test, remediation of identified vulnerabilities begins. The duration needed to implement recommendations and corrective actions to mitigate identified vulnerabilities varies based on the complexity of the required tasks, the volume of findings requiring attention, and/or other constraints specific to the project. 

Remediation testing validates identified vulnerabilities that have been successfully remediated, providing independent confirmation that remediated measures have been implemented in a manner that prevents exploitation. 

Testing frequency 

Security testing cannot be a one-off activity. To be effective, projects must operationalize this process and repeat it at regular intervals. It is also critical to foster cooperation between security, operation, and development teams – a process known as Security in CI / CD.
